The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, March 26, 2004 				 Bengal stake support for Tata coke project
 SUTANUKA GHOSAL																								Calcutta, March 25: The Bengal government has decided to pick up a stake in the coke oven plant being set up by the Tatas in Haldia. 																								State commerce and industry minister Nirupam Sen has directed the West Bengal Industrial Development Corporation (WBIDC) to pick up an initial 5 per cent stake in the proposed one-million-tonne metcoke plant. 																								Tata Iron and Steel Company (Tisco) may have to chip in with Rs 1,000 crore for the plant.																								Bengal had earlier made similar investments in the Rs 1,600-crore Mitsubishi PTA Plant, South Asian Petrochemicals and others. 																								Strategic investments by the government is extremely important. It shows that the government is keen about the project. The promoter also gets a lot of encouragement. The coke oven plant being set up by the Tatas is a major investment in the state. So the government is keen to pick up a strategic stake in the project, said a senior state government official.																								Bengal had invested Rs 433 crore in the Rs 5,170-crore Haldia Petrochemicals project. The government currently owns 43 per cent of the company.																								Tisco has already started feasibility studies for the plant. The company plans to blend imported coking coal with its captive coking coal mined in Jharkhand to feed the proposed coke plant.																								The company has identified the site for the project after several rounds of talks with the Haldia Development Authority. 																								The Bengal government has also decided to make strategic investments in agro and food-processing, information technology and IT enabled services and infrastructure.																								WBIDC is picking up stakes in Calypso (a food-processing company), Imaco Limited (produces air pre-heater baskets), Bengal Pragati and others.																								The corporation has decided to restrict equity funding to strategic areas and big projects only and generally focus on lending.																								WBIDC has disbursed Rs 80 crore in 2003-04. The corporation has recovered around Rs 60 crore in the current fiscal.
